Phase 4 Dashboard — Bug Fix List

The dashboard is partially working but has many visual, functional, and structural issues. Fix all of the following. Read the old dashboard at legacy/dashboard.py for the correct implementations — copy faithfully, don’t improvise.

CRITICAL STRUCTURAL ISSUES:

1. cmd() function missing plugin_id — The platform JS cmd() function sends {command, params} but the new /api/command endpoint expects {plugin_id, command_type, params}. The old cmd() didn’t need plugin_id because there was only one bot. Now it does. Either:
   (a) Have cmd() accept a plugin_id parameter: cmd(‘btc_15m’, ‘start’, {mode: ‘continuous’})
   (b) Or have the plugin JS override cmd() to inject plugin_id automatically
   Check the /api/command route handler to see what field names it expects and make cmd() match.
1. saveSetting() namespacing — The old saveSetting(‘trading_mode’, mode) saved a flat key. The new system needs namespaced keys: ‘btc_15m.trading_mode’. Check that saveSetting properly namespaces the key, and that the /api/config POST handler stores it correctly. The plugin’s setTradingMode already does saveSetting(‘btc_15m.trading_mode’, mode) — verify this works end-to-end.
1. Content bounds / scrolling — The #contentWrap must be bounded between the header and tab bar. The old CSS was:
   #contentWrap { position: fixed; top: 58px; left: 0; right: 0; bottom: 76px; overflow-y: auto; overscroll-behavior-y: contain; -webkit-overflow-scrolling: touch; padding: 8px 12px; }
   But the header height changes when the mode strip is added (adds ~40px). The old dashboard dynamically measured header height. Check that the top offset of contentWrap accounts for the actual header height including the mode strip. If the mode strip makes the header taller, use padding-top on contentWrap equal to the header’s actual height, or use a JS measurement on load.
1. Header height — The old dashboard used padding-top on contentWrap that matched the sticky header’s total height (including safe area inset for iOS notch). With the mode strip adding height, this needs to be recalculated. The old value was approximately:
   padding-top: calc(env(safe-area-inset-top) + [header content height])
   Or the header used padding-top: env(safe-area-inset-top) and contentWrap.top was set dynamically.

